VALUES
(19, 112, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'light in the darkness', 31, 52, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'אור (or, H216) - light, illumination. In Hebrew thought, light often symbolizes divine presence and guidance. This term emphasizes that the upright are not left in despair, but rather receive God''s illuminating truth and direction even in difficult times.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H216", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for light."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'he is gracious, and full of compassion', 54, 92, 'question', 'Reflection on God''s Character', 'How does understanding God as ''gracious'' and ''full of compassion'' influence your view of His actions in your life? In what ways can you reflect these attributes in your relationships with others, especially during challenging times?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'A good man sheweth favour, and lendeth:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Cross-reference to Generosity', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 22:9, which states, "He who is generous will be blessed, for he gives some of his food to the poor." Both verses emphasize the virtue of generosity, suggesting that a truly good character is demonstrated through acts of kindness and support toward others. This connection enhances the understanding of a ''good man'' as one who actively engages in benevolent actions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 22:9", "description": "Highlights the blessing associated with generosity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'he will guide his affairs with discretion.', 40, 82, 'question', 'Reflection on Discretion', 'What does it mean to guide one''s affairs with discretion in the context of faith? How can we apply the principle of discretion in our daily decision-making to align with God’s will? Reflecting on this can help us consider the balance between wisdom and action in our own lives.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'A good man sheweth favour, and lendeth:', 0, 39, 'theology', 'The Nature of Goodness', 'This passage suggests that true goodness is marked by active kindness and generosity. Many scholars believe that the Biblical definition of goodness extends beyond mere moral purity to include acts of service and support for others, reflecting God''s character. This aligns with Jesus’ teaching in Luke 6:35 about loving one''s enemies and doing good, which emphasizes a comprehensive view of righteousness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Luke 6:35", "description": "Jesus teaches about love and goodness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'he will guide his affairs with discretion.', 40, 82, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'נָבַן (naban, H5046) - to be wise, to understand, to be skillful. This Hebrew term underscores the notion of wisdom in managing one’s affairs, indicating that a good person not only acts with kindness but also applies discernment and prudence in their dealings, reflecting a deeper understanding of God''s principles.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5046", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Surely he shall not be moved for ever', 0, 37, 'theology', 'Stability of the Righteous', 'This phrase emphasizes the enduring nature of the righteous in God''s eyes. Many scholars believe that the assurance of being ''not moved forever'' reflects a profound truth about divine protection and stability. This aligns with the biblical theme that God sustains those who trust in Him, as seen in Psalm 125:1, which states that those who trust in the Lord are like Mount Zion, unshakeable. This suggests that a life rooted in faith has eternal implications.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalm 125:1", "description": "Discusses the stability of those who trust in the Lord."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'the righteous shall be in everlasting remembrance', 39, 88, 'connection', 'Eternal Remembrance', 'This phrase connects with Revelation 20:12, where the names of the righteous are written in the Book of Life. The promise that the righteous will be remembered forever highlights the importance of living a life aligned with God''s will. Such remembrance signifies more than just recollection; it implies honor and reward in God''s eternal kingdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Revelation 20:12", "description": "Discusses the Book of Life and the remembrance of the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Surely he shall not be moved for ever', 0, 37, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'מָהֵר (maher, H4116) - to be moved, shaken. This Hebrew term conveys the idea of instability. In this verse, it assures that the righteous, rooted in faith, will remain steadfast and unshaken amidst life''s adversities, illustrating God''s promise of security to those who trust in Him.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4116", "description": "Strong''s number for the term related to being moved or shaken."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'the righteous shall be in everlasting remembrance', 39, 88, 'question', 'Reflection on Remembrance', 'In what ways does the promise of ''everlasting remembrance'' influence how you live your daily life? How does this assurance of eternal recognition by God shape your actions and priorities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'He shall not be afraid of evil tidings:', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Fear and Trust in God', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 112:1, which begins, ''Blessed is the man that feareth the Lord.'' Here, the contrast between fear of God and fear of evil tidings highlights a believer''s security in divine trust. The ''evil tidings'' can refer to any distressing news; yet, the righteous remain steadfast because their fear of God outweighs worldly fears.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 112:1", "description": "Highlights the connection of fearing God versus fearing worldly troubles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'his heart is fixed, trusting in the Lord.', 40, 81, 'theology', 'Foundation of Trust', 'Many scholars believe that the phrase ''his heart is fixed'' indicates a deep, unwavering commitment to God. This reflects the biblical teaching that trust in the Lord is foundational for a righteous life. The heart''s fixation on God suggests a reliance on His promises and character, which is essential for spiritual stability amidst life''s uncertainties.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of a heart fixed on God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'trusting in the Lord.', 60, 81, 'greek', 'Trust in Hebrew', 'בָּטַח (batach, H982) - to trust, to be confident, to be bold. This Hebrew term implies a deep-seated reliance on God that transcends mere belief. It encompasses a sense of security and safety that believers find when they place their confidence in the Lord''s faithfulness.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H982", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for trust."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'He shall not be afraid of evil tidings:', 0, 39, 'question', 'Facing Fear with Faith', 'What does it mean to trust in the Lord when faced with troubling news? In what ways can you cultivate a heart that remains unshaken, despite the chaos of life around you? Reflect on how this verse challenges you to redefine your response to fear.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'His heart is established', 0, 24, 'theology', 'Heart''s Establishment', 'The phrase ''His heart is established'' reflects a profound theological truth about stability and steadfastness in faith. Many scholars believe this signifies the believer''s reliance on God for strength, paralleling texts like Isaiah 26:3, which promises perfect peace to those whose minds are steadfast. This suggests a divine assurance that undergirds the righteous amidst challenges.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Isaiah 26:3", "description": "This verse emphasizes the peace given to those who trust in God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'he shall not be afraid', 26, 48, 'connection', 'Fearlessness in Trust', 'The assurance of ''he shall not be afraid'' connects with Philippians 4:6-7, where believers are encouraged to not be anxious but to present their requests to God, promising peace in return. This connection highlights a recurring biblical theme where trust in God alleviates fear, reinforcing the notion that God''s sovereignty dispels anxiety.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 4:6-7", "description": "This passage offers comfort against anxiety through prayer."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'until he see his desire upon his enemies', 50, 90, 'question', 'Desire upon Enemies', 'What does it mean to see ''his desire upon his enemies''? How does this shape our understanding of justice and vengeance in a Christian context? Reflecting on this may lead you to consider God''s ultimate justice versus personal vindictiveness, urging you to seek divine perspective rather than human retaliation.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'He hath dispersed, he hath given to the poor;', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Generosity in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 19:17, which states, ''He who is generous to the poor lends to the Lord, and He will repay him for his good deed.'' This connection highlights the biblical principle that acts of generosity towards the needy are not only commendable but are seen as direct service to God, with promises of divine recompense. Such generosity is a hallmark of the righteous.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 19:17", "description": "Emphasizes the virtue of giving to the poor."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'his righteousness endureth for ever;', 46, 82, 'theology', 'Eternal Righteousness', 'This passage suggests that the righteousness of the believer is not temporary but eternal. Many scholars believe this reflects the nature of God''s righteousness, which is unchanging and everlasting. It emphasizes the idea that righteous deeds have eternal significance in God''s economy, aligning with Romans 2:6-7, where it speaks of God rewarding each according to their deeds.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 2:6-7", "description": "Discusses God''s reward for righteous deeds."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'his horn shall be exalted with honour.', 83, 121, 'question', 'Understanding Exaltation', 'What does it mean for one''s ''horn'' to be exalted? In biblical symbolism, a ''horn'' often represents strength and power. How does this imagery shape our understanding of the honor bestowed upon the righteous? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper insights about the nature of divine honor and strength in the life of a believer.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'The wicked shall see it, and be grieved;', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Wicked''s Despair', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 10:28, which states, ''The hope of the righteous shall be gladness: but the expectation of the wicked shall perish.'' Both verses illustrate the contrast between the fate of the righteous and the wicked, emphasizing the ultimate despair that the wicked will experience when faced with the triumph of the righteous. The connection highlights the theological theme of divine justice.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 10:28", "description": "Contrast between the hope of the righteous and the wicked"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'he shall gnash with his teeth, and melt away:', 41, 86, 'theology', 'Imagery of Destruction', 'This imagery reflects a common biblical theme regarding the fate of the wicked. Many scholars believe this suggests not only physical anguish but also spiritual torment, indicating a profound separation from God''s presence. The gnashing of teeth is often associated with regret and despair, illustrating the consequences of sin and rebellion against God, as seen in Matthew 13:42.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 13:42", "description": "Context of gnashing teeth in judgment"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 112, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'the desire of the wicked shall perish.', 87, 125, 'question', 'Nature of Desire', 'What does it mean for the desires of the wicked to perish? How might this inform our understanding of what constitutes true fulfillment? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper insights into the nature of righteousness and the fleeting nature of sinful desires, prompting questions about what we truly seek in life.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Praise ye the Lord.', 0, 19, 'connection', 'Call to Worship', 'This phrase echoes the recurring call to worship found in multiple Psalms, such as Psalm 146:1, ''Praise the Lord! Praise the Lord, O my soul!'' The repeated exhortation to praise highlights the importance of worship in the life of believers and serves as a reminder of our duty to exalt God''s name. It reinforces the communal aspect of worship, inviting all who serve the Lord to join in this act of praise.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 146:1", "description": "A similar call to praise the Lord."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Praise, O ye servants of the Lord,', 20, 54, 'theology', 'Servanthood in Worship', 'Many scholars believe that this verse emphasizes the role of believers as servants of the Lord, illustrating a fundamental relationship in Christian theology. Servanthood implies submission and dedication, urging believers to actively participate in worship. This relationship reflects the nature of God as both sovereign and personal, inviting His followers to engage intimately with Him through acts of praise.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of servanthood in praise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'praise the name of the Lord.', 55, 83, 'greek', 'Name of God', 'שֵׁם (shem, H8034) - name, reputation, fame. In biblical contexts, the ''name'' of the Lord encapsulates His character and authority. This reflects the belief that invoking God''s name is not merely a verbal act but an acknowledgment of His presence and attributes. Thus, praising His name signifies glorifying His nature and works.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8034", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''name.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'Praise ye the Lord.', 0, 19, 'question', 'Understanding Praise', 'What does it mean to genuinely praise the Lord in our daily lives? Considering this call to praise, how can we incorporate worship into our routines, ensuring that our actions reflect our reverence for God''s name?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Blessed be the name of the Lord', 0, 31, 'connection', 'Praise of God''s Name', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Proverbs 18:10, which states, ''The name of the Lord is a strong tower; the righteous run to it and are safe.'' Both verses emphasize the importance of the Lord''s name as a source of blessing and safety. This connection matters as it shows the consistent theme in Scripture of the Lord’s name being a refuge for believers.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 18:10", "description": "Highlights the protective nature of the Lord''s name."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'from this time forth and for evermore', 32, 69, 'theology', 'Eternal Nature of Praise', 'Many scholars believe this phrase suggests the eternal significance of worshipping God. The idea of praising Him ''from this time forth and for evermore'' reflects the Christian understanding of God''s unchanging nature and the perpetual obligation of His followers to glorify Him in all circumstances. This aligns with the doctrine of God’s eternal presence and faithfulness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the ongoing nature of worship in relation to God''s eternal character."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Blessed be the name of the Lord', 0, 31, 'greek', 'Hebrew Blessing', 'בָּרוּךְ (baruch, H1288) - blessed, praised. This Hebrew word conveys a deep sense of gratitude and acknowledgment of God''s goodness. It indicates not just a verbal blessing but an active recognition of God’s attributes and actions. This highlights the importance of intentional praise in the believer''s life.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1288", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for blessed."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'from this time forth and for evermore', 32, 69, 'question', 'Understanding Eternal Praise', 'What does it mean to praise God ''from this time forth and for evermore''? How can we incorporate this continual attitude of worship into our daily lives, reflecting on God''s eternal nature and our relationship with Him?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'From the rising of the sun unto the going down of the same', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Universal Praise', 'This phrase echoes the call for universal worship found in Malachi 1:11, which states that from the rising of the sun to its setting, God''s name shall be great among the nations. This connection highlights the global aspect of God''s glory and the expectation of continuous praise from all creation, emphasizing that worship is not confined to a specific location or time.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Malachi 1:11", "description": "This verse calls for worship from all nations, similar to Psalm 113:3."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'the Lord’s name is to be praised', 59, 91, 'theology', 'Nature of Worship', 'This passage suggests that worship is an essential aspect of the believer''s life, reflecting a core Christian doctrine that recognizes God’s sovereignty and holiness. Many scholars believe that praise is not merely an act but a lifestyle, indicating that every moment of the day is an opportunity to honor God, aligning with the teachings of the Westminster Catechism, which states that the chief end of man is to glorify God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Westminster Catechism", "description": "A foundational statement on the purpose of human existence in relation to God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'From the rising of the sun', 0, 26, 'question', 'Daily Praise', 'What does it mean to actively praise God from the moment the sun rises until it sets? How can this practice transform your daily routine and awareness of God''s presence in every moment?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'the Lord’s name is to be praised', 59, 91, 'greek', 'Hebrew Significance', 'שֵׁם (shem, H8034) - name, reputation, fame. In this context, ''name'' signifies not just the title of God but encompasses His character and authority. The act of praising His name is thus an acknowledgment of who He is and all He represents.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8034", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''name''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'The Lord is high above all nations', 0, 34, 'connection', 'Divine Sovereignty', 'This phrase resonates with Isaiah 40:22, which states that God sits above the circle of the earth, emphasizing His supreme authority over creation. Both verses highlight God''s exalted position, affirming His sovereignty over all nations and peoples. Recognizing God''s high status encourages believers to trust in His omnipotence amid worldly chaos.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 40:22", "description": "Illustrates God''s sovereign authority over the earth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'and his glory above the heavens.', 36, 68, 'theology', 'God''s Glory', 'This verse suggests that God''s glory is not just present in the heavens but transcends them, which many scholars believe reflects the idea of God''s incomprehensibility and majesty. The Westminster Shorter Catechism states that ''man''s chief end is to glorify God,'' pointing to the belief that all creation exists to witness and reflect His glory.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Westminster Shorter Catechism", "description": "Defines the purpose of humanity in relation to God''s glory."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'The Lord is high above all nations', 0, 34, 'question', 'Understanding God''s Authority', 'What does it mean for God to be ''high above all nations'' in our contemporary context? How can recognizing God''s ultimate authority over nations shape our understanding of global events and our response to them as believers?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Who is like unto the Lord our God,', 0, 34, 'connection', 'Unique Nature of God', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Exodus 15:11, ''Who is like you, O Lord, among the gods?'' This connection emphasizes God''s unparalleled nature and sovereignty, reinforcing His uniqueness and supremacy over all creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 15:11", "description": "Highlights God''s unmatched character among the divine."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'who dwelleth on high,', 35, 56, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty', 'The phrase ''who dwelleth on high'' suggests God''s transcendence and sovereignty over the universe. Many scholars believe this indicates that God exists beyond the limitations of creation, asserting His authority over all things, both spiritual and earthly.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Who is like unto the Lord our God,', 0, 34, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Uniqueness', 'In light of this declaration, what does it mean for you personally that there is no one like the Lord? How does this truth influence your understanding of His authority in your life?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'who dwelleth on high,', 35, 56, 'greek', 'Understanding ''dwelleth''', 'שָׁכַן (shakan, H7931) - to dwell, settle, abide. This term conveys not only the idea of residing but also of establishing presence, which highlights God''s intimate connection with creation while also being exalted above it.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7931", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Who humbleth himself to behold', 0, 30, 'theology', 'God''s Humility', 'This phrase highlights the profound humility of God, who, despite His exalted position, chooses to engage with His creation. Many scholars believe this reflects the nature of God''s grace, emphasizing that He is not aloof or distant but actively involved in the world. This concept is echoed in the New Testament, where Jesus exemplifies humility through His life and ministry.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Philippians 2:6-8", "description": "Paul speaks of Christ''s humility in becoming human."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'to behold the things that are in heaven, and in the earth!', 21, 79, 'connection', 'Heaven and Earth', 'This phrase connects with Genesis 1:1, which states, ''In the beginning God created the heaven and the earth.'' The connection underscores God''s sovereignty over all creation, both heavenly and earthly. It highlights that God''s gaze encompasses all realms, affirming His omnipotence and the significance of His attention to both the grandeur of heaven and the humility of earth.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:1", "description": "God''s creation of heaven and earth establishes His authority over all."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Who humbleth himself', 0, 20, 'greek', 'Greek Insight: Humility', 'ταπεινόω (tapeinóō, G5013) - to make low, to bring down. This term emphasizes the action of lowering oneself, contrasting with the typical view of power and authority. God''s choice to humble Himself is a radical expression of His love and accessibility, presenting a model for believers in how to engage with others.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5013", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term related to humility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'to behold the things that are in heaven, and in the earth!', 21, 79, 'question', 'Divine Attention', 'What does it mean for God to ''behold'' both heaven and earth? How does this shape our understanding of His involvement in our lives? Reflecting on God''s attentiveness can deepen our appreciation for His care and the significance of our earthly experiences in light of His divine perspective.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'He raiseth up the poor out of the dust,', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Scriptural Echoes', 'This phrase resonates with Luke 1:52, where Mary praises God for ''bringing down the mighty from their thrones and exalting those of humble estate.'' Both passages highlight God''s preferential option for the marginalized, emphasizing His active role in uplifting the downtrodden. This connection illustrates a consistent biblical theme of divine justice and mercy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 1:52", "description": "Mary''s Magnificat reflects God''s concern for the humble."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'lifteth the needy out of the dunghill;', 44, 82, 'theology', 'God''s Compassionate Action', 'This verse underscores a fundamental aspect of God''s character: His compassion towards the needy. Many scholars believe that this reflects the doctrine of God''s grace, where He not only sees the plight of the poor but actively intervenes to uplift them, thereby demonstrating His love and care for humanity, especially the marginalized.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'He raiseth up the poor out of the dust,', 0, 39, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'עָלָה (alah, H5927) - to go up, ascend. This Hebrew term indicates not just a physical elevation but also a spiritual or social lifting, suggesting transformation and restoration for those in despair. The use of this term in the context of uplifting the poor emphasizes God''s role as a redeemer.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5927", "description": "Indicates the concept of ascent and elevation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 113, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'lifteth the needy out of the dunghill;', 44, 82, 'question', 'Reflective Application', 'What does it mean for us to lift others from their ''dunghill'' today? In what practical ways can we embody God''s care for the needy in our communities, and how does this challenge our perspectives on social justice and compassion?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');